  title: Official Decree Conferring Titles upon Geum Ui
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A Proclamation:

    Without rewards for virtue, virtue cannot flourish. Thus must we cultivate a culture that honors the good, and only after all acclaim one as worthy should we employ the worthy. This is the true teaching of honoring the virtuous. Therefore, when bestowing radiant honors, one must await the fitting person.

    The Official Geum Ui embodies purity crystallized within like uncut jade and raw gold—those who see him recognize his rare brilliance. His talents shine outward like white rainbows and crimson lightning, inspiring awe in all who behold him. In his early service to the Eastern Palace, he sang with the grace of the wild goose, and in the Southern Province, he briefly submitted to humble administrative duty. Soon he ascended to the clouds, entering the golden registers of court. In his pursuits of learning, he stands unrivaled, achieving ever greater heights without rigidity or excess. In the Ministry of Selection, his judgments prove fair and just, earning him the mirror of golden clarity to reflect his discerning eye. In attendance at the imperial gates, his instruction grows ever more diligent, and through his guidance, error is transformed and genuine sincerity revealed.

    His brush wields five-fold authority, his cap rises with singular distinction. In teaching at the Academy, he awakens sudden brilliance in his students, rivaling the rapid transformation of the seventy disciples. In recruiting talent through the rites ministry, has he not brought forth scholars worthy of immortality itself? Twice he has counseled in matters of succession, each time displaying steadfast resolve. Entering the inner sanctum of the dragon gate, though he chafes at distance from the throne, he proclaims the celestial scrolls of the phoenix tail with authority. In all matters of human consequence, he presents his counsel within, and in all affairs of state security, he speaks forth without hesitation. Where he perceives need, he acts without delay, bearing heavy responsibility with resolute dedication.

    Given such service to the realm, it is fitting to grant exceptional honors. The rank of Grand Commandant stands beneath the Prime Minister; we allow him to hold all three positions. The post of Academician is the noble station of immortals themselves; we permit him to retain dual appointments. The splendor of his name and authority extends even unto grass and tree, which tremble at his word. Thus we issue this edict of grace, that he may walk the halls of power as counselor, securing the stability of the realm. His stratagems, silent as movements behind the curtain, determine victory at distant remove. His poems surpass those of the great masters, as though eternal verses bloom in the palace gardens. Let him also retain the rank of Draftsman of Imperial Decrees, supreme among the scholars of state.

    Hear now this decree: Fang Xuanling and Du如晦became prime ministers, each excelling in strategy or in judgment; yet you unite such talents. Zhao Cui and Zhao Dun earned renown for virtue through both reverence and affection; yet you perfect both these virtues. Go forth now to your duties, and be forever faithful to honor.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Eastern Palace (東宮) reference evokes the tale of Han Gaozu, who attempted to replace his heir, only to relent when moved by the intervention of wise hermits. The allusion suggests steadfast loyalty that transcends political vicissitude.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Five-fold Authority' (五花判) refers to the Tang practice where five officials jointly signed imperial documents, symbolizing collaborative governance and broad-based authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'singular distinction' of his official cap alludes to the imperial censor's insignia, marking him as one who bears the weight of moral judgment.
  - key: ''
    value: The comparison to poets like Xie Tiao evokes the literary excellence of court scholars, suggesting that Geum Ui's talents extend to cultural and intellectual spheres beyond mere administration.
  - key: ''
    value: Fang Xuanling and Du Ruohui represent the ideal of complementary talents in governance—one excelling in strategy, the other in decisive judgment—suggesting Geum Ui embodies both qualities.
